{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T06-37-27-041Z","slug":"developer-workstation-blast-radius","locale":"es","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T06:37:50.613Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-09--developer-workstation-blast-radius/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-09--developer-workstation-blast-radius/es/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/developer-workstation-blast-radius/es/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T06-37-27-041Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"2ea2b0fa3efd5f31a991b8add09b755aea04ca443ae149a0b177d9569acefeef","outputHash":"0d09c2737b9bd835ee9fa337952cd0809502294ac8dd4039f2609343a4c61815","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that the real security problem on developer laptops is “blast radius” – the tendency for any code that runs as the user to inherit all of the user’s privileges – and offers a pragmatic, tutorial‑style guide to shrink that exposure without crippling productivity. It proposes a four‑layer defense (isolation, secret handling, detection, egress control) and focuses on concrete tools: using narrowly‑mounted Dev Containers to isolate project tooling, replacing sprawling plaintext *.env* files with encrypted or managed secrets (e.g., VarLock), and inserting canary tokens for detection, all illustrated with code snippets and best‑practice checklists. The tone is instructional, peppered with survival‑ist metaphors (“wet cement”, “blast radius”) to frame the problem as a manageable engineering trade‑off rather than an all‑or‑nothing security overhaul. The intended audience is software engineers and engineering managers who want actionable steps to harden developer workstations while preserving a smooth development experience.","totalInputTokens":37062,"totalOutputTokens":5965,"totalCacheReadTokens":10496,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":21922,"totalCost